ore bantering than condemning.  If it had been altogether condemning she in her moody caprice would have walked away proudly, severing him without saying a word in that behavior typical to those whose youth had been besieged in the worst of ridicule.      \par     "I don't know.  Sometimes I want to be different.  Sometimes the glare of the sun gives me a headache."\par     "You aren't feeling sick now, are you?"\par     "No."\par     "Then take them off."\par     "Ask me in a nice way."\par     "Please do it.  Do it please.  Do please it."  He laughed.\par     Her womanliness flowed in and she took them off, begrudgingly eager to please and a little excited that someone should take an interest--even a critical interest-- in the mundane aspects of her life.  She felt sexual energy hit her in a large wave since two wills clashing against each other was a sexy thing.  They followed Rick who had run toward a hotdog stand.\par     "Corndogs -- won't you have one, Gabriele?" asked the former MF.\par     "I don't eat meat, you know."\par     "Well, you should, you know.  Its why the brain size of man is so much bigger than his hominoid predecessors."\par }\pard \widctlpar\nooverflow\faroman\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs22     "I doubt that much evolution can come from a corndog.  And if I had a bigger head it would probably explode all over the place.  Wouldn't that be a pretty sight?"\par }\pard \widctlpar\nooverflow\faroman\rin0\lin0\itap0 {\fs22      " Maybe your grandpa slaughtered your pet pig at his farm--something made you this sensitive.  I wouldn't know about that but I do know that as long as the killing isn't man to man it's just nature's checks and balances."  She saw that truth lay there and not wishing to dismiss it , she nodded.  She wondered if he had put too many limits on his theme.  Maybe murder and wars were checks and balances of man on man too. He smiled with a flippant boyish mischievousness. "You know, by walking from the museum you have sq